{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"45b3c5f3-a674-4f0a-912c-9701292550fe","content":"Yes, both properties are correct and they work well together in .NET MAUI on .NET 10.\n\n**`ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`** — This iOS platform-specific adjusts the page's padding so content doesn't overlap the notch, home indicator, or status bar. You'll need the namespace:\n\n```xml\nxmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;\n         assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n```\n\n**`IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"`** — This lets a specific view (like a Grid with a background image) extend edge-to-edge, *ignoring* the safe area padding set by the page. This is the correct way to get a full-bleed background while keeping other content safe.\n\n**Typical pattern:**\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\" ...>\n    <Grid>\n        <!-- Background image extends to edges -->\n        <Image Source=\"bg.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\" />\n\n        <!-- Content respects safe area -->\n        <VerticalStackLayout Padding=\"16\">\n            <Label Text=\"Hello, World!\" />\n        </VerticalStackLayout>\n    </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nYour tutorial's approach is correct for .NET 10.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"18076840-c0c0-4f18-9cc3-3be5d9387609","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI safe area handling on iOS, specifically about two properties:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` - a platform-specific property for ContentPage\n2. `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` - on a Grid for background images\n\nLet me check what I know about .NET MAUI safe area APIs, particularly for .NET 10.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the iOS safe area handling has evolved:\n\n- `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` is an iOS platform-specific that was available in earlier versions. It adjusts the page's padding to respect the safe area insets.\n\n\n- `Page.UseSafeArea` is the iOS platform-specific attached property from `Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific.Page`, available since early MAUI versions. Meanwhile, `IgnoreSafeArea` came later, with .NET 9 introducing significant changes to how safe areas are handled overall.\n\n- For .NET 10, `UseSafeArea` remains the recommended approach for iOS safe area handling, while `IgnoreSafeArea` lets specific views extend beyond the safe area boundaries—useful for edge-to-edge backgrounds and similar scenarios.\n\n- I'm uncertain about the exact deprecation status of `UseSafeArea` in .NET 9 or whether it was replaced entirely, so I should stick with what I can confirm about the current state.","outputTokens":1052,"requestId":"D448:259D27:1D551EA:20DB114:6A07C02C"},"id":"cd21d8ba-8a8d-4433-8b11-bbdd06b3e30a","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:54:23.340Z","parentId":"51f817a7-a187-4c1e-b138-609244491767"}
